grain of salt, except for a few very large cases.

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:53.200
India's large reserves of thorium, however, explains their interest in using it as fuel.

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:57.840
China also have an interest in thorium, such that it is often produced as a byproduct of

00:02:57.840 --> 00:03:00.640
rare earthbinding and refining.

00:03:00.640 --> 00:03:04.440
As a result of this, there are large reserves of thorium already mine there, which could

00:03:04.440 --> 00:03:06.960
be used as fuel.

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:09.880
Why there is interest in using thorium as a fuel?

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:14.440
There are several reasons why people are interested in using thorium as a nuclear fuel.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:19.800
Abundance of thorium Thorium is roughly three times as abundant as uranium in the earth's

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:20.800
crust.

00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:25.360
This is based on statistical sampling of rocks, not in terms of finding commercial order

00:03:25.360 --> 00:03:26.360
deposits.

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:31.000
However, the world is not currently short of uranium, so the relative abundance of

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:35.400
thorium is not a significant advantage at this time.

00:03:35.400 --> 00:03:37.760
Some countries have a lot of it.

00:03:37.760 --> 00:03:42.440
Some countries in India in particular have far more thorium than they do uranium.

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:47.240
As a result of this, they see thorium as a strategic and security advantage in giving them

00:03:47.240 --> 00:03:51.440
a sovereign independent supply of energy.

00:03:51.440 --> 00:03:56.040
Thorium breeder reactors are simpler than uranium breeder reactors.

00:03:56.280 --> 00:04:04.600
Thorium 232 to uranium 233, the a neutron bombardment, is analogous to converting uranium 238

00:04:04.600 --> 00:04:10.680
to various plutonium isotopes in terms of turning fertile isotopes into fizzile ones.

00:04:10.680 --> 00:04:15.080
Listen again to the previous episode on fast neutron reactors if you need to refresh

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:20.360
your on those, but fast neutron breeder reactors are more expensive and difficult to design

00:04:20.360 --> 00:04:24.080
and operate than thorium reactors.

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:28.280
Thorium can be used in reactors similar to certain types which have been in large-scale

00:04:28.280 --> 00:04:33.280
commercial use for decades, and so are less complex and expensive than, for example, a

00:04:33.280 --> 00:04:36.320
liquid sodium-fast neutron reactor.

00:04:36.320 --> 00:04:41.320
No new technologies required to use thorium in commercial power reactors.

00:04:41.320 --> 00:04:44.400
Supposed lower nuclear weapons potential.

00:04:44.400 --> 00:04:48.200
Some people are of the view that there is less potential for creating nuclear weapons if

00:04:48.200 --> 00:04:51.800
thorium is used as fuel than is the case for uranium.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:54.840
However, I am not convinced of this as an argument.

00:04:54.840 --> 00:05:01.360
Commercial uranium cycle power reactors are not suitable for creating weapons-grade plutonium.

00:05:01.360 --> 00:05:06.160
Plutonium or enriched uranium are required for thorium cycle reactors.

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:10.920
A country which has a large number of thorium cycle reactors will need either uranium

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:17.400
enrichment or plutonium processing facilities while natural uranium reactors require neither.

00:05:17.440 --> 00:05:22.880
On this basis, the least problematic fuel would appear to be natural uranium.

00:05:22.880 --> 00:05:25.000
What is thorium breeding?

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.880
As mentioned previously, thorium by itself cannot be used as a nuclear fuel.

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:35.400
By using plutonium or enriched uranium as driver elements, however, thorium can be converted

00:05:35.400 --> 00:05:41.240
to fizzile uranium 233 which can be used to sustain a reaction.

00:05:41.240 --> 00:05:45.240
There are different configurations for the fuel elements which I won't go into here as

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:47.480
this would require too much detail.

00:05:47.480 --> 00:05:53.560
Essentially, though, a mix of thorium 232 and either plutonium or enriched uranium 235

00:05:53.560 --> 00:05:56.120
would be loaded into the reactor.

00:05:56.120 --> 00:06:00.600
The reaction would be started off by the plutonium or uranium 235.

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:07.400
Bombardment of the thorium 232 by neutrons would gradually convert it to uranium 233.

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:12.840
As uranium 233 accumulated, it would also efficient and contribute to the power output,

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:16.840
making up for the using up of the plutonium and uranium 235.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:21.320
By the end of the life of the fuel, all or nearly all of the energy would be coming from the

00:06:21.320 --> 00:06:24.280
created uranium 233.

00:06:24.280 --> 00:06:29.240
The fuel is then removed from the reactor and reprocess to recover the remaining uranium 233.

00:06:30.040 --> 00:06:34.680
This uranium 233 may then be used as a driver fuel for a fresh fuel load.

00:06:35.560 --> 00:06:39.880
For reactors that are refueled continuously while online, that is while operating,

00:06:40.520 --> 00:06:45.880
fresh fuel is continuously fed in and used fuel extracted rather than being distinct

00:06:45.880 --> 00:06:48.040
loading and unloading phases of operation.

00:06:49.240 --> 00:06:50.520
Breeding ratio.

00:06:50.520 --> 00:06:56.360
The amount of uranium 233 created in this process will depend upon the reactor and fuel design.

00:06:57.080 --> 00:07:02.840
This may vary from not much uranium 233 generated all the way up to theoretically at least,

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:08.760
more uranium 233 being extracted from the spent fuel than the amount of driver fuel used to

00:07:08.760 --> 00:07:09.640
start the reaction.

00:07:10.520 --> 00:07:13.160
That is, the breeding ratio would be greater than one.

00:07:13.880 --> 00:07:19.320
However, this has not been demonstrated and most fuel cycles assume that a continual source of

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:24.120
driver fuel will be required, generally from some sort of uranium cycle reactors.

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:27.560
What sorts of reactors can use thorium?

00:07:28.120 --> 00:07:34.120
Most of the types of nuclear reactors we have discussed so far in the series can use thorium fuel to some extent.

00:07:34.760 --> 00:07:37.240
However, some are more suitable for it than others.

00:07:38.760 --> 00:07:42.680
pH WRs, that is heavy water reactors, including can do.

00:07:43.480 --> 00:07:48.520
Large-scale commercial pressurized heavy water reactors have been used for decades around the world.

00:07:49.240 --> 00:07:53.880
These have run on natural uranium but are also well suited to using thorium fuel due to their

00:07:53.880 --> 00:07:55.240
efficient use of neutrons.

00:07:55.960 --> 00:08:00.840
India is one of the countries using this type of reactor and they have done a great deal of R&D

00:08:00.840 --> 00:08:02.200
on using them with thorium.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:08.040
A typical thorium fuel for them would consist of 5% reactor-grade plutonium,

00:08:08.040 --> 00:08:13.880
plus thorium, about 80% of the energy generated would come from the thorium portion of the fuel.

00:08:14.520 --> 00:08:17.880
An alternative to plutonium would be low enriched uranium.

00:08:18.680 --> 00:08:22.520
None of the commercial reactors of this type are currently running on thorium,

00:08:22.520 --> 00:08:26.120
but this is an area of ongoing research, particularly in India.

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:33.400
HTR, high temperature gas-cooled reactors, as mentioned in a previous episode,

00:08:33.400 --> 00:08:37.160
some of the experimental gas-cooled reactors have used thorium fuel.

00:08:37.800 --> 00:08:45.080
Examples of these are the AVR and THTR 300 reactors in Germany in the 1960s to the 1980s.

00:08:45.800 --> 00:08:50.600
These were pebble bed reactors in which the fuel was in the form of spheres of fuel,

00:08:51.480 --> 00:08:58.200
enriched uranium and thorium, plus a graphite moderator, and formed into billiard ball size spheres.

00:08:59.560 --> 00:09:02.040
The reactors were cooled by helium gas.

00:09:02.680 --> 00:09:07.960
Pebble bed reactor technology is being revived for the small modular reactor market,

00:09:07.960 --> 00:09:10.200
but these doer ones don't involve thorium.

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:16.360
Moulton salt reactors. Moulton salt reactors use molten salt as a coolant.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:22.760
When used with dissolved thorium fuel, the salt would be a fluoride salt in order to be chemically

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:28.680
compatible with thorium. To be used in a thorium fuel cycle, they would normally have a graphite

00:09:28.680 --> 00:09:34.040
moderator. From the perspective of thorium, there are two variants of molten salt reactor

00:09:34.040 --> 00:09:39.800
that are of interest. One type contains a fuel inside separate fuel pins, like in most other

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:44.360
reactor types. The other dissolves a fuel in the molten salt coolant.

00:09:45.640 --> 00:09:49.800
In the latter case, there would be a chemical processing loop that extracts unwanted

00:09:49.800 --> 00:09:54.840
fission products that is elements that were created in the reaction that we don't want present,

00:09:55.480 --> 00:10:02.360
and uranium 233 from the salt on a continuous basis. Moulton salt reactors were discussed in

00:10:02.360 --> 00:10:08.680
another episode as they can use many types of fuel besides thorium. Not all developers of molten

00:10:08.680 --> 00:10:13.800
salt reactors are convinced they are well suited to using thorium. With the head of one company

