A practical thorium fuel cycle requires reprocessing of spent fuel, something that is not required

00:12:41.560 --> 00:12:47.080
for a once-through fuel cycle with uranium, and is done with uranium in only a few countries today.

00:12:48.120 --> 00:12:55.000
This reprocessing is another additional cost. The uranium 233 and leftover thorium in spent fuel

00:12:55.080 --> 00:13:02.040
contain highly radioactive isotopes such as uranium 232 and thorium 228, which make reprocessing

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:07.160
difficult and expensive. This is not to say that thorium does not have some potential in the

00:13:07.160 --> 00:13:12.440
long run. Rather, it means that the advantages of thorium are offset by problems which come along

00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:18.280
with it. Overall, the balance of present in most countries favors using uranium in a once-through

00:13:18.360 --> 00:13:25.800
fuel cycle. Thorium in India, an example use case, India is probably the prime example of a

